Down to 5.9% in July and more likely to track down than up in the coming months as rates go up (bringing down demand) and supply chain bottlenecks ease.

If inflation continued for July-Oct at the same rate as last year, the final value would be 5.91%. I am hesitantly optimistic that inflation will be a bit slower over the same period this year because of Fed actions, seasonality, and the beginning of a natural resolution to inflation. So I'm increasing my weight on bin 3.

Index value for July 22 = 295.646. Inflation slowed, as seasonality, among other things, kicked in. Inflation may finally be tapering.(295.646/281.617 - 1) * 100% = 4.98% over 9 months. 3 more months to go.(295.646/294.680 - 1) * 100% = 0.33% mom inflation from June to July; compare to 0.74% mom inflation for May-Jun 22.At 0.33% mom inflation for July - Oct, inflation would reach ((1.0498 * 1.0033^3) - 1) * 100% = 6.02%. Based on seasonality alone, as seen last year, I'd expect mom inflation for July-Oct to be similar to that for June-July, perhaps with a bump from Sept to Oct, so I expect inflation to end up close to 6.0% at this point. With inflation starting to resolve, though, I'll guess that <6.0% is more likely.To reach 7.5% inflation, we'd need to see the index at 281.617 * 1.075 = 302.738, equivalent to ((302.738 / 295.646) ^ (1/3) - 1) * 100% = 0.79%. That doesn't seem plausible at this point, with seasonality kicking in and inflation starting to taper.I also can't picture inflation falling to 4.5% or lower, but it is possible that prices could fall.

This is really a pretty silly question. The whole point of the core inflation measurement is to take out food and energy because food and energy are volatile over the short term. But if you're going to look at a 12 month average, you might as well have food and energy included. Everybody uses food and energy (the other thing you could maybe say that about is housing) so why exclude them for no good reason?

This is my first forecast on this question. My projection is based on the 7 months of data we have so far in the forecast period plus a projection that mom core inflation will hold relatively steady in the remaining 5 months of the forecast period.Index at 292.506 for May 22, 290.846 for April 22, 281.617 for Oct 21. (292.506/281.617 - 1) * 100% = 3.87% over 7 months.(292.506/290.846 - 1) * 100% = 0.57% mom inflation for April-May 22. Mar-April was at 0.53%, so a very slight acceleration was seen in May.https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPILFENSAt 0.57% mom inflation, we'd expect to see 2.88% inflation from May through October, and annual inflation in Oct to be at 6.86%.Bins 1 and 2: Out.Bin 3: Core inflation would have to slow dramatically for the question to resolve in bin 3. The index would need to stay under 1.06*281.617 = 298.514. This would be equivalent to mom inflation staying under 0.41% for the remainder of the forecast period. Given that May mom inflation was at 0.57% and April at 0.53%, this doesn't seem likely to me.Bin 4: I think this bin is most likely. Inflation has been holding fairly steady, and if it does, Oct core inflation should be around 6.4%-7.1%.Bin 5: To reach 7.0%, the index would need to reach 281.617*1.075 = 302.738 in Oct. That would require (302.738/292.506 -1) * 100% = 3.50% inflation from May to Oct, equivalent to 0.69% mom inflation. Given that we saw 0.57% mom inflation for Apr-May, up from 0.53% for Mar-Apr, it seems possible to me that we could see 0.69% mom inflation from now to Oct.

April inflation rate is likely going to be about the same as March's inflation rate. The last 6 months average inflation is about 7.5%, and the only way that 12 month average inflation in October can be below 6% is if we average less than 4.5% YoY inflation for the next 6 months after May's report. (We'd have to see almost 1/5 lower YoY inflation for the next 6 months)
